6. A magnetic resonance imaging system for producing tomographic images of multiple slices of an object, in which two kinds of magnetic resonance signals having different frequencies are induced based on chemical shifts, by saturating spins that have one of two peak resonant frequencies, and by utilizing spins that have the other peak resonant frequency, said magnetic resonance imaging system comprising: 
a frequency error measuring device for measuring an error of a peak resonant frequency of spins at each of slice positions specifying multiple slices; 
a maximum value extracting device for extracting a maximum value from among errors of peak resonant frequencies with the peak resonant frequencies observed between the peak resonant frequency of the spins to be used for imaging and the peak resonant frequency of the spins to be saturated; 
an exciting device for exciting spins using an exciting signal whose frequency deviates from the peak resonant frequency of the spins to be used for imaging towards the peak resonant frequency of the spins to be saturated by an equivalent of a value calculated by adding the maximum value to a theoretical change in a peak resonant frequency stemming from a chemical shift; and 
a saturating device for saturating the excited spins.

7. A magnetic resonance imaging system for producing tomographic images of multiple slices of an object, in which two kinds of magnetic resonance signals having different frequencies are induced based on chemical shifts, by saturating spins that have one of two peak resonant frequencies, and by utilizing spins that have the other peak resonant frequency, said magnetic resonance imaging system comprising: 
a frequency error measuring device for measuring an error of a peak resonant frequency of spins at each of slice positions specifying multiple slices; 
a maximum value extracting device for extracting a maximum value from among errors of peak resonant frequencies with the peak resonant frequencies observed between the peak resonant frequency of the spins to be used for imaging and the peak resonant frequency of the spins to be saturated; 
a difference calculating device for calculating differences of an error of a peak resonant frequency of spins in each slice from errors of peak resonant frequencies of spins in the other slices; 
an exciting device for when one of the differences of the errors of peak resonant frequencies exceeds a predetermined threshold with the peak resonant frequencies observed between the peak resonant frequency of the spins to be used for imaging and the peak resonant frequency of the spins to be saturated, exciting spins using an exciting signal whose frequency deviates from the peak resonant frequency of the spins to be used for imaging towards the peak resonant frequency of the spins to be saturated by an equivalent of a value calculated by subtracting the threshold from a value calculated by adding the maximum value to a theoretical change in a peak resonant frequency stemming from a chemical shift, and for when none of the differences exceeds the threshold, exciting spins using an exciting signal whose frequency deviates from the peak resonant frequency of the spins to be used for imaging towards the peak resonant frequency of the spins to be saturated by an equivalent of a value calculated by adding an error of a peak resonant frequency of spins in a slice concerned to a theoretical change in a peak resonant frequency stemming from a chemical shift; and 
a saturating device for saturating the excited spins.
